ce:section.ce:para:
The coatings incorporated with soluble Li salts showed decreased barrier performance compared to a typical epoxy primer, which often has capacitive behavior even at very low frequencies. Before exposure to any artificial weathering, the initial impedance spectra of both a control epoxy coating and the one with lithium oxalate salt are shown in Fig. 2
                        . Both systems show capacitive behavior at higher frequencies, and non-steady behavior at lower frequencies showing sudden drop of impedance moduli. The non-steady behavior indicates fast penetrating of water through the coating system, and less restrictive ion flow, caused by having the soluble and heterogeneous Li salt phase in the system. This decreased barrier performance can also be observed through impedance spectra from coatings being exposed to both salt spray and constant immersion (Figs. 3 and 4

                        ), corresponding with others’ findings [5,9,15]. In addition, a drastic change of the barrier property can be demonstrated by the depressed low-frequency impedance modulus of the samples without exposure (0 hours spectrum in Fig. 4). The depressed spectrum indicates non-steady nature of the measurement resulting from fast changes in the barrier performance (within the time frame of the low-frequency impedance measurement). Within 20 minutes i.e., the last 4 points of the spectral measurement, the impedance modulus dropped about two decades (from 3.18 × 109 to 4.51 × 107 ohm). The low-frequency impedance modulus change appeared stabilized between 10,000 and 100,000 ohms and eventually dropped as low as around 1000 ohms. Despite the very low impedance indicating the barrier loss, the coating itself did not show any sign of failure or visible defects. These changes of low-frequency impedance indicate coatings barrier performance being compromised, which in authors’ opinion requires further investigation to ensure the benefit of Li salt's inhibition outweighs its effects on barrier performance.
